Inverse design of programmable shape-morphing kirigami structures.

Interesting poinst so far in the introduction.

  • The kinematics of a tessellation behaves as a single degree-of-freedom system.
  • For inverse design methods, the sensitivity study of periodic square kirigami tessellation was conducted to investigate how hinge width and gap width affect the in-plane and out-of-plane behavior.
  • Magnetically actuated kirigami was proposed in order to realize target shape-morphing under specific magnetic excitation.
  • The inverse design of kirigami tessellation under inhomogeneous boundary conditions.
  • Inverse design for shape-morhping structures combines two tasks: (1) a forward method that can accurately predict the deformed shape under certain external stimuli, and (2) an inverse optimization framework that can efficiently find the acceptable solution to achieve the target shape.
  • FEA (Recuerdos de Vietnam (T n T) ) is used to predict the deformed shape takin into account the geometric and material nonlinearity. For the second task, evolutionary algorithm (EA) can be used as a technique to find satisfactory solution to a global optimization problems.
  • This study proposes a two-step optimization framework. (1) Utilizes a constrained kinematic optimization to generate the cut pattern that allows the kirigami tessellation to deploy into the target shape while satisfying geometric compatibility. (2) The generated cut pattern is used as the initial cut guess and is further optimized considering elasticity.

Mechanics

The neo-Hookean method is used to capture the hyperplastic constitutive behavior of rubber sheet, and geometric nonlinearities were take into consideration. The kirigami is modeled as rigid panels connected by thin ligaments, where it is assumed that all deformations are localised at the ligament parts, while the square domain is considered as rigid body as shown next.

Each ligament can be seen as a rotational spring that is solely subjected to bending moment, and the rotation of each ligament is penalised by elastic energy, which is determined by bending stiffness (Como la stiffnes matrix de FEA?)
As shown above, a square unit deforming uniaxially under the force f is tracked by the degree-of-freedom given by an opening angle . The applied uniaxial stress generates an identical bending moment M at each hinge.

Two steps of inverse design framework

GA (Genetics algorithm) is used to generate multiple kinematically valid cut patterns and use scripted modelling to transform kinematic models into finite element models and obtain the actual deployed shape.
FEA is used to obtain the actual mechanical response.
The mutation rate is defined as a range of values between 0.01 and 0.1, based on the best fitness of a one generation.
